k = 3
i = 0
set = {1}
i = 1
set = {1,2}
i = 2
set = {1,2,3}
i = 3
1 already exists

Return:

true
Why Sliding Window Works?

For

|i - j| <= k

Only elements within the last k positions matter.

So maintain:

Window Size = k

and remove older elements.

Complexity
Time: O(n)
Space: O(k)
Interview Summary
Approach	Time	Space
Brute Force	O(n²)	O(1)
HashMap (Index Tracking)	O(n)	O(n)
Sliding Window + HashSet	O(n)	O(k)
Which Approach Should You Give?
If interviewer asks for optimal:

HashMap

Number → Last Index

is the most intuitive solution.

If interviewer asks to optimize space:

Use

Sliding Window + HashSet

with O(k) space.

Key Trick

Instead of storing all duplicates:

Store the latest index

Then check:

Current Index - Previous Index <= k
